This notebook is a hands-on exploration of core image processing concepts using OpenCV. It loads an image from disk and immediately treats it as what it actually is under the hood  a NumPy array which means every pixel is just a number you can read and overwrite directly. The code demonstrates this by accessing specific pixel coordinates and manually setting them to red (0, 0, 255 in BGR).
From there it covers spatial operations: extracting image dimensions (height, width, channels), cropping regions of interest using NumPy array slicing (top-left, top-right, bottom-left, bottom-right quadrants), and painting entire regions a solid color by assigning values to slices.
The color space section is the meatiest part , it splits the image into its R, G, B channels individually, visualizes each one, then merges them back. It then converts to HSV (Hue-Saturation-Value) and L*a*b* color spaces, splitting and displaying each channel. This matters because different color spaces are useful for different tasks. HSV is better for color-based segmentation, L*a*b* is perceptually uniform.
Finally it covers thresholding converting to grayscale, applying Gaussian blur to reduce noise, then applying binary and inverse binary thresholds to segment the image into black and white regions. There's also a short webcam capture loop that reads 5 frames and saves them as numbered PNGs.
